sec.p:
In this work we use the LSTM classifier as a black box that describes the quality of each play based on a desired Field Goal percentage (FG%) for each play. As shown in Figure 5 our data allow the aggregation of plays along several types of plays. In the next step we provide the user feedback to explain how a specific play could be modified to improve its quality, that is, improve the $\text{FG} \%$ above a given threshold. In particular we focus on how individual input features contribute to the model's prediction. Formally, consider a machine learning model, such as an LSTM classifier f, defined as: $f(\mathbf{X}): \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$
where $\mathbf{X}=\left(x_{1}, x_{2},. ., x_{n}\right)$ represents the vector of input features. The goal of explainability is to provide a mathematical mechanism to quantify the influence of each feature $x_{n}$ on the output $f(\mathbf{X})$. A common approach to achieve this involves decomposing the model's prediction into contributions attributed to each input feature:
\begin{equation*}
x_{n}, f(\mathbf{X})=\phi_{0}+\sum_{m=1}^{n} \phi_{m}
\end{equation*}
